HOUSE RESOLUTION NO. 384
BY REPRESENTATIVE MILLER
HEALTH: Requests the Louisiana State University School of Health Sciences to conduct
certain studies to identify associations between environmental risk factors and
maternal health outcomes
1 A RESOLUTION
2 To urge and request the Louisiana State University School of Health Sciences to conduct
3 certain studies to identify associations between environmental risk factors and
4 maternal health outcomes and to report its findings by July 1, 2027.
5 WHEREAS, women and the unborn are exquisitely sensitive to chemical toxicants,
6 therefore, a precautionary approach is needed; and
7 WHEREAS, the absence of health effects does not mean no health effects; and
8 WHEREAS, limitations of health surveillance include out-migration, disease latency,
9 health reporting gaps, data privacy rules, small populations, and ecological fallacies in terms
10 of using parish level data to infer no problem at the local level, and complex exposures; and
11 WHEREAS, there are gaps in our knowledge of additive, synergistic, and cumulative
12 effects of complex exposures to chemical mixtures through the different life phases; and
13 WHEREAS, the gaps in environmental monitoring in communities adjacent to
14 industrial and agricultural areas limit our ability to connect the dots between exposure and
15 health outcomes; and
16 WHEREAS, regulatory standards, risk assessments, and oversight tend to focus on
17 one chemical, exposure route, or source at a time; and
18 WHEREAS, there has been only one peer reviewed study on the association between
19 reproductive outcomes and environmental hazards in Louisiana as opposed to seventy
20 related studies in Texas; and
